2019-12-21 07:45:04	FromGitter	<j8r> I prefer LXC over classic VMs if  I need a Linux sandbox :)
2019-12-21 07:49:46	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> docker <3
2019-12-21 07:52:33	FromGitter	<j8r> docker is only designed to run a single service
2019-12-21 07:52:48	FromGitter	<j8r> not a whole OS with the init system
2019-12-21 07:53:04	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> uhhhh
2019-12-21 07:53:27	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> docker uses LXC
2019-12-21 07:53:41	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> and is almost exclusively used to run whole OSes
2019-12-21 07:53:59	FromGitter	<j8r> try to run systemd or OpenRC inside docker, you will see
2019-12-21 07:55:14	FromGitter	<j8r> you have to do hacks like this: https://hub.docker.com/r/jrei/systemd-debian
2019-12-21 07:56:07	FromGitter	<j8r> don't do this in a production environment 💀
2019-12-21 07:56:17	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> hacks like using an image designed for that purpose?
2019-12-21 07:56:52	FromGitter	<j8r> no, you have to create mounts with the underlying system, and run as privileged therefore
2019-12-21 07:57:24	FromGitter	<j8r> so the container isn't really isolated anymore
2019-12-21 07:58:26	FromGitter	<j8r> Docker is designed to be stateless (we have to create mounts to keep data), LXD/LXC is both
2019-12-21 07:59:11	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> Docker is designed to be stateless for very good reasons
2019-12-21 08:00:00	FromGitter	<j8r> maybe, but that's not always adapted to all use cases
2019-12-21 08:00:14	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> nor is any other technology
2019-12-21 08:00:43	FromGitter	<j8r> that's why LXC/LXD is good for a VM-like environment :)
2019-12-21 08:00:55	FromGitter	<j8r> and Docker for application development
2019-12-21 08:01:27	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> why bother running a Linux VM on a Linux host?
2019-12-21 08:01:44	FromGitter	<j8r> to not pollute it.
2019-12-21 08:01:51	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> with?
2019-12-21 08:02:49	FromGitter	<j8r> with databases, applications, etc. And it is to test other distributions
2019-12-21 08:03:26	FromGitter	<j8r> I want to test something that needs root - I don't want to mess up my system, sure
2019-12-21 08:04:29	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> what would you test that needs root?
2019-12-21 08:04:51	FromGitter	<j8r> Ansible for instance
2019-12-21 08:04:58	FromGitter	<j8r> or database installation
2019-12-21 08:05:28	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> what risk is there in installing either of those?
2019-12-21 08:06:43	FromGitter	<j8r> because if it doesn't work, my system can be impacted
2019-12-21 08:07:49	FromGitter	<j8r> Ansible modify system used, ntp, hosts, init services
2019-12-21 08:09:15	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> and in your testing, did you find that purging the package reverted all those changes?
2019-12-21 08:09:29	FromGitter	<j8r> it wont, it's not only about packages
2019-12-21 08:09:56	FromGitter	<j8r> there are always configurations files that will stay
2019-12-21 08:10:11	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> they shouldn't if the package is purged
2019-12-21 08:10:25	FromGitter	<j8r> Ansible is about installation, not uninstallation
2019-12-21 08:10:43	FromGitter	<j8r> It ensures everything is setup
2019-12-21 08:10:57	FromGitter	<j8r> sure you can uninstall with it
2019-12-21 08:11:28	FromGitter	<j8r> but if tasks modify files, you will have to do it manually to revert
2019-12-21 08:12:30	FromGitter	<j8r> that's always good to have a safe, reproducible, controlled sandbox
2019-12-21 08:12:59	FromGitter	<j8r> it avoids to have "it works on my PC", "but not on yours" - lol
2019-12-21 08:14:08	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> that's sort of the point of ansible though, to ensure that the system reaches a known state
2019-12-21 08:14:58	FromGitter	<j8r> indeed, and we don't want to have this state locally
2019-12-21 08:15:19	FromGitter	<j8r> that's why having a VM s close as the production is good
2019-12-21 08:16:19	<--	alexherbo283 (~alexherbo@aputeaux-651-1-261-138.w86-249.abo.wanadoo.fr) has quit (Quit: The Lounge - https://thelounge.chat)
2019-12-21 08:17:38	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> okay. I'm probably not going to be in a hurry to run multiple services on the same machine though
2019-12-21 08:19:36	FromGitter	<j8r> for instance, databases doesn't work very well in Docker, even less on K8S
2019-12-21 08:20:06	FromGitter	<j8r> That's why we stick with the classic way to do for this
2019-12-21 08:20:28	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> you're probably alone in thinking databases don't work well in Docker/K8s
2019-12-21 08:20:42	FromGitter	<j8r> no, I don't think so
2019-12-21 08:21:00	FromGitter	<j8r> virtualization layers add IO latency
2019-12-21 08:21:09	FromGitter	<j8r> and that's fairly important for databases
2019-12-21 08:21:22	FromGitter	<j8r> furthermore, a database is stateful
2019-12-21 08:21:32	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> so you have a volume
2019-12-21 08:21:49	FromGitter	<j8r> mounted locally? This break the whole point of K8S
2019-12-21 08:22:07	FromGitter	<j8r> and you can no longer destroy the node like this
2019-12-21 08:22:26	FromGitter	<j8r> or perhaps using CEPH, but it adds latency, too
2019-12-21 08:23:06	FromGitter	<j8r> you are right, you can, but IMO it's not as good as for stateless applications
2019-12-21 08:25:29	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> Docker is great for stateful applications. You just need to extrapolate the state out using mounting in various ways. You can have multiple database processes accessing the same database information, but you should still introduce sharding for very large databases
2019-12-21 08:25:58	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> Mounts don't have to be local
2019-12-21 08:26:17	FromGitter	<j8r> but then, what's the point of K8S?
2019-12-21 08:26:41	FromGitter	<j8r> a dedicated hosts for the databases will perfectly do the job
2019-12-21 08:27:00	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> What do you mean? k8s uses mounts
2019-12-21 08:27:00	FromGitter	<j8r> and will have optimum performace
2019-12-21 08:27:27	FromGitter	<j8r> For me local mounts are not an option
2019-12-21 08:27:44	FromGitter	<j8r> and remote mounts add latency.
2019-12-21 08:27:50	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> For production, sure. Local mounting is used mainly for development
2019-12-21 08:28:21	FromGitter	<Daniel-Worrall> remote mounts are usually found in the same datacenter, they're only remote in the context of the host
2019-12-21 08:30:17	FromGitter	<j8r> Some databases can already use sharding/replication natively (ElasticSearch, PostgreSQL, Redis) ⏎ No need to have a redundant FS like Ceph then
2019-12-21 08:31:56	FromGitter	<j8r> I just find the advantages less interesting for this kind of apps
2019-12-21 08:36:54	FromGitter	<j8r> What we have do with prometheus is running is on a dedicated node, alone, with a local mounted volume
2019-12-21 08:37:07	FromGitter	<j8r> Because else, there is performance impact
2019-12-21 08:38:44	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> you've benchmarked the alternatives?
2019-12-21 08:39:42	FromGitter	<j8r> On Amazon, the best is to use the local EBS storage
2019-12-21 08:40:29	FromGitter	<j8r> anyway, it not critical data, that's fine
2019-12-21 08:40:51	FromGitter	<j8r> other topic, Alpine 3.11  :)
2019-12-21 08:41:06	FromGitter	<j8r> there is Crystal 0.31.1 on it
2019-12-21 08:41:33	FromGitter	<j8r> Need to do a PR for 0.32.1
