2019-12-21 12:21:28	FromGitter	<nsuchy> Does Crystal have something like this yet? https://devblogs.microsoft.com/typescript/announcing-typescript-3-7/#optional-chaining
2019-12-21 12:21:50	FromGitter	<Blacksmoke16> `.try?`
2019-12-21 12:22:09	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> ^
2019-12-21 12:22:10	FromGitter	<Blacksmoke16> https://crystal-lang.org/api/master/Object.html#try(&)-instance-method
2019-12-21 12:22:24	FromGitter	<nsuchy> so that's the equivalent?
2019-12-21 12:22:31	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> yes
2019-12-21 12:24:19	FromGitter	<randiaz95> Lol, its so funny seeing MSFT using `ish`
2019-12-21 12:24:34	FromGitter	<randiaz95> my thought is Microsoft thought highly of themselves and always used intense language
2019-12-21 12:25:40	FromGitter	<randiaz95> I personally stick to begin rescue end
2019-12-21 12:26:07	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> `try` doesn't swallow exceptions, just `nil`
2019-12-21 12:26:38	FromGitter	<randiaz95> interesting...
2019-12-21 12:27:02	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> it's most useful for dealing with nilable types
2019-12-21 12:27:22	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> within the `try` block, the value is guaranteed to be non-`nil`
2019-12-21 12:27:55	FromGitter	<randiaz95> nilable type is something like Int8|nil ?
2019-12-21 12:28:10	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> or `arr.find { ... }.try do |value|`
2019-12-21 12:28:28	FromGitter	<randiaz95> interesting, so find returns nil if it doesn't find anything
2019-12-21 12:28:55	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> yes, and also whatever method you call in the block doesn't yell at you because it's not defined on `Nil`
2019-12-21 12:29:35	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> the alternative is `if(a = arr.find { ... ])`
2019-12-21 12:30:18	FromGitter	<tenebrousedge> you have to do an assignment and a test for falsity
2019-12-21 12:51:08	FromGitter	<j8r> I usually prefer doing `if value = arr.find { ... }.try` compared to `arr.find { ... }.try do |value|`
2019-12-21 12:51:36	FromGitter	<j8r> I find `try` is useful on single line statements
